Get the data into a usable format and perform at least three different aspects of feature engineering.

Examples:¶

*Normalize the Corpus

*Bag of Words Modeling

*Bag of N-Grams Modeling

*Topic Modeling

*Clustering

In this project I hope to look at the differences between the Democratic, Republican, and 'Other' party inagural speeches. The other parties consist of a grouping of parties prior to the inception of the modern day republican and democratic parties.

I will use unsupervised learning throughout the course of the project rather than predefinded classification in order to determine if there are any innate characteristics to the data, rather than forcing them into predetermined trends.

#convert inaugural into a pandas dataframe with each speech as a row
speeches= []
for fileid in inaugural.fileids():
    year, president= fileid.split('-')
    speeches.append((year, president, inaugural.raw(fileid)))

def remove_numbers(corpus):
    norm_corpus= re.sub(r'\b[0-9]+\b\s*', '', corpus)
    return norm_corpus

Cluster and Document Similarity Across Parties¶

The first distinguishing feature I would like to look at is the clustering of the speeches. Through the clustering method I hope to see if there are characteristics that place each different party's speeches into respective categories, and if those categories align with the different parties. I perfect result would be 3 clusters with the democratic, republican, and other speeches each falling into it's own cluster.

Top Words for Each Party¶

Here I would like to look at the top words used in the speeches for each of the parties. When normalizing the speeches I left the words 'no' and 'not' in the context to denote sentiment better and look to see if those words show up more in one party than another and they tend to denote a negative tone.

I will create a word cloud for each party to better visualize the differences in the top words.

In [25]:
#tokenize into words
wt= nltk.word_tokenize

def word_tokens_15(array):
    string= ' '.join(array)
    words= wt(string)
    counter= Counter(words)
    most_common= counter.most_common(15)
    most_common= dict(most_common)
    return most_common

def word_tokens_30(array):
    string= ' '.join(array)
    words= wt(string)
    counter= Counter(words)
    most_common= counter.most_common(30)
    most_common= dict(most_common)
    return most_common

The sentiment analysis shows more difference in the speeches than the other previous evaluation methods. Democratic inagural speeches are predominately negative, and much more so than the other two political party groups at almost half of the speeches falling into this category. Republicans take the prize for the positive speeches at over 65 percent of their speeches falling into this sentiment category, and the other speeches are a close second looking at 41 percent of their speeches being positive.

In conclusion, though there are not much difference in the words used for the different parties inagural speeches, there is a distinct difference in the context in which those same words are used.
